ors working in higher education, communities, schools, and practitioners who want to learn how to better integrate the arts in their practice to critically and creativity communicate, teach, make meaning, uncover, and involve. The book contextualises the place and role of the arts in society, adult education, higher education and knowledge creation, outlines current arts-based theories and methodologies and provides examples of visual and performing arts practices to critically and creatively see, explore, represent, learn and discover the potential of the human aesthetic dimension in higher education teaching and research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdult education. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh  aStorefront 101 course.  aactive dialogic processes.  acivic engagement.  acontemporary university.  acultural engagement.  acultural theorisations.  ademocracy.  afreedom.  ahigher education.  ahuman aesthetics.  ainstrumentalism.  aknowing-through-doing approach.  aknowledge creation.  alifelong learning.  apop-up galleries.  asocial theorisations.  ateacher education.  auniversity-based adult education.  avisual arts.1 aAllen, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButterwick, Shauna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClover, Darlene E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClover, Darlene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCranton, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtmanski, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroen, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https: